**Product Requirements**

**Document**

GCSE Interactive Test Platform

Multi-Subject Extension: Biology, Chemistry & Beyond

Version 1.0 · February 2026 · Confidential

Based on the Physics Motion & Graphs prototype

1\. Executive Summary

This PRD defines a reusable, multi-subject GCSE interactive test
platform. The architecture extends the existing Physics Motion & Graphs
prototype into a generalised system capable of serving Biology,
Chemistry, and any future GCSE subject with subject-specific interaction
patterns, marking rules, and content structures.

The core insight is that while the question engine, state machine,
timer, marking pipeline, and results dashboard are subject-agnostic,
each GCSE subject requires bespoke interaction components. Physics needs
interactive SVG graphs. Biology needs labelling diagrams, process
sequencing, and image-based identification. Chemistry needs equation
balancing and molecular structure interactions.

This document specifies the platform architecture, the Biology subject
module in detail (as the first extension), the abstraction layer that
enables new subjects, and a phased delivery roadmap.

2\. Problem Statement

Students preparing for Edexcel GCSE exams lack high-quality, interactive
digital mock tests that replicate the authentic exam experience.
Existing tools are either static PDF papers, generic quiz apps that miss
subject-specific interaction patterns, or expensive proprietary
platforms.

The Physics prototype demonstrated that a **scenario-based, multi-part
question structure** with interactive graphs, a real marking engine, and
worked solutions produces a significantly better learning experience
than traditional approaches.

The challenge is extending this to subjects with fundamentally different
interaction requirements without rebuilding the platform for each one.

3\. Goals & Success Metrics

3.1 Goals

1.  Extend the platform to support Biology as the first additional
    subject within 4 weeks of starting development.

2.  Architect the system so adding a new subject requires only: (a)
    subject-specific interaction components, (b) scenario JSON data,
    and (c) a marking adapter --- no changes to the core platform.

3.  Maintain the same Apple HIG design quality and exam authenticity
    established in the Physics prototype.

4.  Support Edexcel specification alignment with topic tagging,
    misconception tracking, and mark scheme fidelity.

3.2 Success Metrics

  ------------------------ ------------------------ ----------------------
  **Metric**               **Target**               **Measurement**

  Time to add Biology      \< 4 weeks dev time      Sprint tracking
  module                                            

  Time to add 3rd subject  \< 2 weeks dev time      Sprint tracking

  Question accuracy        100% correct answers     QA review by teacher
                           verified                 

  Student completion rate  \> 80% finish full mock  Analytics

  Score correlation        Within 10% of real exam  Student self-report
                           score                    
  ------------------------ ------------------------ ----------------------

4\. Platform Architecture

The platform separates into a subject-agnostic core and pluggable
subject modules. This is the key architectural decision that enables
scalability.

4.1 Core Platform (Subject-Agnostic)

These components are shared across all subjects and must not contain any
subject-specific logic:

-   App Shell --- state machine (welcome → active → review → results),
    routing, session management

-   Welcome Screen --- subject selector, mode selector (Practice/Exam),
    timer presets, start flow

-   Test Runner --- scenario navigation, part sequencing, progress
    tracking, flagging

-   Timer --- countdown, warning/critical states, auto-submit

-   Review Screen --- answered/unanswered/flagged part grid,
    jump-to-part

-   Results Dashboard --- score display, percentage, grade, topic
    breakdown, per-question review

-   Marking Pipeline --- answer validation router that delegates to
    subject-specific markers

-   Feedback Panel --- correct/incorrect/partial display, worked
    solution renderer

-   Design System --- CSS variables, typography, components (buttons,
    cards, inputs, badges)

4.2 Subject Module Interface

Each subject registers a module that implements the following interface:

  --------------------- -------------------------------------------------
  **Property**          **Description**

  **id**                Unique subject identifier (e.g. \'physics\',
                        \'biology\', \'chemistry\')

  **name**              Display name (e.g. \'Biology\')

  **icon**              Subject icon or emoji

  **examBoard**         Target exam board and tier info

  **scenarios**         Array of scenario JSON objects (question data)

  **components**        Map of custom interaction component renderers
                        (e.g. \'diagram_label\', \'equation_balance\')

  **markingAdapters**   Map of custom answer type markers (extends core
                        MCQ/numeric markers)

  **topicTree**         Hierarchical topic structure for results
                        breakdown
  --------------------- -------------------------------------------------

4.3 Rendering Pipeline

When the Test Runner encounters a question part, it checks the part
type. If the type is handled by the core (mcq, numeric_with_unit,
graph_reading, calculation), it renders the standard component. If the
type is subject-specific, it looks up the component in the subject
module\'s components map and delegates rendering to it.

This means the core never needs to know about Biology diagrams or
Chemistry equations --- it simply asks the subject module to render the
appropriate interaction.

4.4 File Structure

The project structure extends as follows for each new subject:

src/subjects/physics/ --- Physics module (existing prototype)

src/subjects/biology/ --- Biology module (new)

scenarios/ --- Biology scenario JSON files

components/ --- DiagramLabel.js, ProcessSequence.js, etc.

marking/ --- Biology-specific marking adapters

index.js --- Module registration (implements Subject Module Interface)

5\. Biology Module --- Detailed Specification

Biology is the first extension subject. It introduces interaction
patterns not present in Physics: labelling diagrams, ordering biological
processes, identifying structures from images, and constructing
explanations with key terms.

5.1 Edexcel Biology Specification Alignment

The Biology module targets Edexcel GCSE Biology (1BI0) or Combined
Science Biology content. The prototype will cover the following
high-frequency exam topics:

  -------- ---------------------- ---------------------- -------------------
  **\#**   **Topic Area**         **Key Content**        **Interaction
                                                         Types**

  1        Cell Biology           Animal/plant cell      Diagram label, MCQ,
                                  structure, organelles, calculation
                                  microscopy             

  2        Organisation           Digestive system,      Diagram label,
                                  enzymes, heart &       process sequence,
                                  circulation            MCQ

  3        Infection & Response   Pathogens, immune      MCQ, keyword match,
                                  response, vaccination  explain

  4        Bioenergetics          Enzymes, rate of       Graph reading,
                                  reaction graphs        calculation, MCQ

  5        Photosynthesis         Word equation, leaf    Keyword match,
                                  structure, limiting    diagram label,
                                  factors                graph reading,
                                                         explain

  6        Respiration            Aerobic/anaerobic,     Keyword match, MCQ,
                                  word equations, energy explain
                                  release                

  7        Gas Exchange           Lung structure,        Diagram label, MCQ,
                                  alveoli, diffusion,    explain
                                  surface area           

  8        Nervous System         Reflex arc,            Diagram label,
                                  sensory/relay/motor    process sequence,
                                  neurons, reaction time MCQ, calculation

  9        Ecology                Food chains, sampling, Calculation, data
                                  biodiversity           table, MCQ

  10       Genetics & Evolution   DNA, inheritance,      Punnett grid, MCQ,
                                  Punnett squares,       explain
                                  natural selection      
  -------- ---------------------- ---------------------- -------------------

5.2 Biology-Specific Question Types

These are the interaction components unique to Biology that must be
built as part of the subject module. They do not exist in the Physics
prototype.

5.2.1 Diagram Labelling

Students are shown a biological diagram (cell, heart, leaf
cross-section, etc.) with numbered blank labels. They select the correct
term for each label from a dropdown or drag-and-drop pool. This is one
of the highest-frequency question types in Biology GCSE exams.

-   Diagram is an SVG or image with positioned label hotspots

-   Each hotspot has a set of answer options (dropdown) or accepts
    drag-drop from a term bank

-   Marking: 1 mark per correct label, no negative marking

-   Partial credit: award marks for each correct label independently

**Data schema:** Each diagram question includes a diagramSpec with image
source, hotspot coordinates (as % of image width/height for
responsiveness), and answer options per hotspot.

5.2.2 Process Sequencing

Students arrange steps of a biological process into the correct order.
Used for mitosis stages, digestive process, immune response, carbon
cycle, etc.

-   Draggable cards with step descriptions

-   Student reorders into correct sequence

-   Marking: full marks for fully correct order; partial credit based on
    number of correctly positioned items or correctly ordered adjacent
    pairs

5.2.3 Keyword Matching / Key Term Builder

Students match key biological terms to their definitions, or fill in
blanks in a passage using terms from a word bank. Extremely common in
1--3 mark questions.

-   Word bank displayed as draggable chips

-   Blanks in a passage or definition list as drop targets

-   Marking: 1 mark per correct placement

5.2.4 Punnett Square Grid

Students complete a Punnett square for a genetic cross. They fill in
alleles in the grid and then answer probability questions based on the
results.

-   Interactive 2×2 or 4×4 grid with editable cells

-   Parent alleles shown on axes

-   Student types offspring genotypes into cells

-   Follow-up calculation: probability/ratio of phenotypes

-   Marking: 1 mark per correct cell or per correct ratio

5.2.5 Graph Reading (Shared with Physics)

Biology also uses graph interpretation heavily (enzyme rate curves,
photosynthesis rate vs light intensity, population growth). The existing
SVG graph component from Physics can be reused directly, with
biology-specific axis labels and data.

-   Reuse the Physics Graph.js component with no modifications

-   Biology scenarios supply different graphSpec data (rate of reaction,
    population curves, etc.)

-   May need to add curve fitting / smooth line mode (Physics prototype
    only uses straight segments)

5.2.6 Explain / Extended Response (Self-Assessed)

Biology exams include 4--6 mark extended response questions. These
cannot be auto-marked reliably. In practice mode, the student writes
their answer, then sees a model answer and a checklist of key points.
They self-assess how many points they covered.

-   Textarea input for student\'s response

-   Model answer with highlighted key points (mark scheme checklist)

-   Student ticks which points they included

-   Marks awarded based on self-assessment (practice mode only)

-   In exam mode: stored as text, not scored, flagged as
    \'teacher-marked\'

