7\. Unified Scenario Data Model

All subjects use the same top-level scenario schema. Subject-specific
fields are nested inside the parts.

  ------------------ ---------------- ------------------------------------
  **Field**          **Type**         **Description**

  **id**             string           Unique scenario ID (e.g. \'bio_01\')

  **title**          string           Scenario display title

  **icon**           string           Emoji or icon reference

  **context**        string           Scenario context paragraph
                                      (exam-style stem)

  **difficulty**     string           \'foundation\', \'higher\', or
                                      \'foundation-higher\'

  **graphSpec**      object \| null   Graph config (reused from Physics).
                                      Null if no graph in this scenario.

  **diagramSpec**    object \| null   Biology-specific: image + hotspot
                                      positions + term options

  **dataTable**      object \| null   Data table shown alongside the
                                      scenario (headers + rows)

  **parts**          Part\[\]         Array of question parts (3--5 per
                                      scenario)
  ------------------ ---------------- ------------------------------------

Each Part object contains: id, partLabel, type, marks, question,
answerSchema, solutionSteps, topicTags, skillTags, misconceptionTags,
and optionally methodMarks. The type field determines which component
renders the answer input and which marking adapter scores it.

8\. Biology Diagram Specification

The diagramSpec object defines how interactive diagrams work. This is
the most complex biology-specific data structure.

  --------------------- ---------------- -------------------------------------
  **Field**             **Type**         **Description**

  **imageSrc**          string           Path to SVG or PNG diagram image

  **imageAlt**          string           Accessible alt text describing the
                                         diagram

  **hotspots**          Hotspot\[\]      Array of label positions with answer
                                         options

  **hotspot.id**        string           Unique hotspot ID (e.g. \'label_1\')

  **hotspot.x**         number (0--100)  X position as percentage of image
                                         width

  **hotspot.y**         number (0--100)  Y position as percentage of image
                                         height

  **hotspot.correct**   string           Correct term ID

  **termBank**          Term\[\]         Array of { id, text } terms available
                                         for selection
  --------------------- ---------------- -------------------------------------

9\. Future Subject Modules

The architecture supports adding any GCSE subject. Below are preliminary
notes for Chemistry and other subjects.

9.1 Chemistry

Chemistry introduces these unique interaction types:

-   Equation Balancing --- student adjusts coefficients in a chemical
    equation until it balances. Marking checks stoichiometric
    correctness.

-   Molecular Structure Builder --- student draws or selects
    dot-and-cross diagrams, covalent bonds, or ionic lattice structures.

-   Periodic Table Reference --- interactive periodic table for looking
    up atomic numbers, groups, and properties.

-   Electrolysis Diagrams --- label anode/cathode, ions, and products.

Chemistry reuses: graph component (rate of reaction curves), diagram
labelling (apparatus, electrolysis cells), numeric+unit calculations
(moles, concentration, Mr).

9.2 Mathematics

Mathematics would require:

-   Equation/expression input --- a structured math input component
    (consider KaTeX or MathQuill for rendering).

-   Coordinate geometry tools --- extend the graph component with line
    drawing, point plotting, transformation tools.

-   Working space --- a scratchpad area for showing algebraic working.

-   Multiple correct forms --- marking must accept equivalent
    expressions (e.g. 2/4 = 1/2 = 0.5).

9.3 English Literature

English is primarily extended writing, so the interactive test format is
less suitable. However, it could support:

-   Extract-based MCQ and short answer questions

-   Quotation identification (match quote to character/theme)

-   PEE paragraph builder (Point, Evidence, Explanation) with
    self-assessment

10\. Non-Functional Requirements

10.1 Performance

-   First meaningful paint \< 1.5 seconds on 4G connection

-   Graph interactions must respond within 16ms (60fps) for smooth
    crosshair tracking

-   Diagram images should be SVG where possible; PNG with lazy loading
    for complex illustrations

-   Total bundle size \< 200KB (excluding images)

10.2 Accessibility

-   WCAG AA compliance minimum

-   Full keyboard navigation for all interactive elements

-   Screen reader support with ARIA labels on graphs, diagrams, and
    custom components

-   Minimum 44px touch targets on all interactive elements

-   Reduced motion support via prefers-reduced-motion media query

-   Dyslexia-friendly option: increase line height, letter spacing;
    offer OpenDyslexic font toggle

-   Font size adjustment (small / medium / large)

10.3 Browser Support

-   Chrome 90+, Safari 15+, Firefox 90+, Edge 90+

-   iOS Safari 15+ (iPad is a common student device)

-   No IE11 support required

10.4 Data & Privacy

-   All data stored client-side only (localStorage or sessionStorage)

-   No user accounts, no server-side storage in v1

-   Optional: export results as JSON or PDF for teacher review

-   Future: optional cloud sync with user consent

